h Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Croy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Orkney): habitational name from any of several places called Croy, for example in Inverness-shire.","Probably also Irish: shortened form of   McCroy  , which is a variant of   McRoy  ."],"variants":[{"name":"McCroy","meanings":["Irish: variant of   McRoy  ."]}]},{"name":"Guillaume","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Germanic.  See  <b>William</b> ."],"variants":[{"name":"William","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Guillaume de Croy was born in 1320, in Brussels, Belgium, his father, Jacques II  le Vieux de Croy, was 33 and his mother, Marie de Picguigny, was 28. He married Isabeau de Renty about 1340, in France. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1365, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1320–1365":"1320–1365","1335–1384":"1335–1384","1335–1377":"1335–1377","1347–1380":"1347–1380","1349–Female":"1349–Surnud","1365–1415":"1365–1415","1288–Male":"1288–Surnud","1292–1367":"1292–1367","1384":"1384","ABT 1349":"umbes 1349","1292":"1292","1380":"1380","Abt 1340":"umbes 1340","1415":"1415